<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I calculate the interval for a time-lapse?", answer: "Divide the total event duration (in seconds) by the number of frames needed. The number of frames equals the desired video duration multiplied by the playback frame rate. For example, to compress a 2-hour sunset into a 30-second video at 24fps: you need 720 frames, so the interval is 7200 seconds / 720 = 10 seconds between shots." },
  { question: "What frame rate should I use for time-lapse video?", answer: "24fps is the cinematic standard and produces smooth, natural-looking time-lapse video. 25fps is the PAL broadcast standard. 30fps is the NTSC standard and gives slightly smoother playback. Higher rates like 60fps are uncommon for time-lapse but can be used for slow-motion playback of the compressed footage." },
  { question: "What is a good interval for cloud time-lapse?", answer: "For fast-moving clouds, use 1-3 second intervals. For slow, wispy clouds, use 5-10 second intervals. For dramatic storm clouds, 2-5 seconds works well. Start with 3 seconds as a safe default for cloud photography and adjust based on cloud speed." },
  { question: "How much storage do I need for a time-lapse?", answer: "Storage depends on file format, camera resolution, and number of frames. A 24MP camera shooting JPEG produces roughly 8 MB per frame; RAW files are about 25 MB each. A 1000-frame time-lapse needs approximately 7.8 GB for JPEG or 24.4 GB for RAW." },
  { question: "How long should a time-lapse video be?", answer: "Most time-lapse videos work best between 10 and 60 seconds. Social media clips perform well at 15-30 seconds. Longer time-lapses of 1-3 minutes can work for dramatic subjects like the Milky Way or a full day sunrise-to-sunset sequence." }
]) %>

